36","1271":"1271","1192":"1192","1249":"1249","1216":"1216","1226":"1226","1236":"1236","1312":"1312","Abt 1255":"circa 1255","1255":"1255","1299":"1299","March 1299":"maart 1299","2 May 1249":"2 mei 1249","Frisby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England":"Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Essex, England":"Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Tilney with Islington, Wisbech, Norfolk, England":"Islington, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1226–March 1299":"about 1226–March 1299","1226–1299":"1226–1299","1216–1271":"1216–1271","–Female":"Deceased","1249–1299":"1249–1299","1255–1312":"1255–1312","1190–1236":"1190–1236","1192–Female":"1192–Deceased","1190":"1190","Abt 1226":"about 1226","Abt 1236":"about 1236","1271":"1271","1192":"1192","1249":"1249","1216":"1216","1226":"1226","1236":"1236","1312":"1312","Abt 1255":"about 1255","1255":"1255","1299":"1299","March 1299":"March 1299","2 May 1249":"2 May 1249","Frisby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England":"Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","Tilney with Islington, Wisbech, Norfolk, England":"Islington, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Foliot","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Italian (Lombardy): variant of   Foglio  . This surname is very rare in Italy."],"variants":[{"name":"Foglio","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Carmine, Dino, Flavio, Julieta, Sal, Salvatore.","Italian: probably from the Latin personal name <i>Folius</i> (which is embodied in the common placename Fogliano)."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Foliot was born about 1226, in Essex, England, United Kingdom, his father, Jordan Foliot III, was 38 and his mother, Margery, was 36. He married Margery Stuteville. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in March 1299, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 74."},"et":{"Abt 1226–March 1299":"umbes 1226–märts 1299","1226–1299":"1226–1299","1216–1271":"1216–1271","–Female":"Surnud","1249–1299":"1249–1299","1255–1312":"1255–1312","1190–1236":"1190–1236","1192–Female":"1192–Surnud","119